# Product Description / Presentation #

AIâ€‘Powered Legal Document Analysis & Contract Negotiation â€” Build Brief
Project Codename: ClauseGuard AI
Product description / presentation
ClauseGuard AI accelerates legal review and negotiation by extracting clauses, scoring risk, proposing redlines, and maintaining an auditâ€‘ready trail of every change. It ingests contracts (NDA, MSA, DPA, SOW, SaaS Terms), maps them to your playbooks and fallback positions, drafts counterâ€‘proposals, simulates counterparty responses, and supports live, collaborative negotiations with citations to policy and precedent. Optional blockchain anchoring provides tamperâ€‘evident proof of document integrity at key milestones.
What it does:
â€¢	Parses DOCX/PDF scans (OCR) into a canonical, structured DocJSON with sections/clauses/definitions/schedules.
â€¢	Detects clause types and obligations, aligns to your playbook tiers (preferred â†’ acceptable â†’ fallback).
â€¢	Calculates risk scores (jurisdictional, regulatory, data, liability) and flags redlines required to reach policy.
â€¢	Generates suggested edits/redlines with plainâ€‘English rationales and citations to prior negotiated language.
â€¢	Runs a negotiation simulator (whatâ€‘if) to preview counterparty pushback across common patterns.
â€¢	Supports multiâ€‘user live sessions with presence, comments, tasks, and approval gates.
â€¢	Anchors versions on a public chain (optional) by hashing content and storing the hash to create evidentiary trails.

Key features:
â€¢	RAGâ€‘grounded analysis over your clause library, policies, precedent contracts, and regulations.
â€¢	Redline editor with sideâ€‘byâ€‘side diff, clause browser, and citation sidebar.
â€¢	Policy engine with jurisdiction packs (e.g., US, EU, UK) and configurable fallback ladders.
â€¢	Eâ€‘signature and CLM handâ€‘off, export back to Word/PDF with tracked changes.
â€¢	Endâ€‘toâ€‘end audit trail (who/what/when/why) and immutable anchors (optional).

Why legal teams love it:
â€¢	Cuts firstâ€‘pass review time from hours to minutes while increasing consistency.
â€¢	Makes risk transparent with explainable rationales and links to precedent.
â€¢	Fits existing CLM/eâ€‘sign flows; optional blockchain proof without exposing contents.
Framework (and why)
LangGraph (orchestration) + LangChain (tools) + RAG (mandatory) with OpenAI + Claude. LangGraph provides deterministic, resumable, humanâ€‘inâ€‘theâ€‘loop negotiation flows with approval gates; LangChain standardizes retrievers, tools, and tracing; RAG grounds extractions and redlines in your policies and precedent. CrewAI can be used during prototyping for role ideation, but production orchestration stays in LangGraph for reliability.
1. BACKEND ARCHITECTURE (extensive)
Core services (FastAPI â€¢ async SQLAlchemy 2.0 â€¢ Pydantic v2):
â€¢	Auth & Tenant: JWT (access/refresh), RBAC (admin/counsel/reviewer/guest), optional SSO (OIDC/SAML), SCIM.
â€¢	Document Ingest: OCR for scans, DOCX/PDF parsers â†’ canonical DocJSON; versioning; virus scan.
â€¢	Clause Extraction: NER + pattern rules to detect clause type (indemnity, liability cap, governing law, DPA, SLA, IP).
â€¢	Evidence/RAG Service: corpus ingestion (policies, playbooks, clause library, precedent contracts, public regs), chunking, embeddings (pgvector), citation resolver.
â€¢	Negotiation Orchestrator (LangGraph): Ingest â†’ Classify â†’ Retrieve â†’ Assess Risk â†’ Propose Redlines â†’ Simulate â†’ HIL Gate â†’ Finalize.
â€¢	Policy Engine: jurisdiction packs, thresholds (cap %, survival days), fallback ladders, forbidden phrases.
â€¢	Collaboration: WebSockets sessions, comments, tasks, presence, approvals with audit trail.
â€¢	Export & CLM: trackedâ€‘changes DOCX/PDF, CLM handâ€‘off (webhooks), eâ€‘signature handâ€‘off.
â€¢	Anchoring (optional): compute content hash (Merkle root) and anchor to public chain via RPC; store tx metadata only.
Data model (PostgreSQL + pgvector):
â€¢	tenants, users, roles, api_keys, oauth_connections
â€¢	documents(id, tenant_id, title, type, status), doc_versions(id, document_id, hash, created_at, author_id)
â€¢	sections, clauses, definitions, schedules (linked to doc_version with offsets)
â€¢	extractions(id, doc_version_id, clause_type, entities jsonb, confidence)
â€¢	playbooks(id, jurisdiction, rules jsonb), clause_library(id, title, text, tags)
â€¢	recommendations(id, doc_version_id, risk_score, rationale, citations jsonb, proposals jsonb)
â€¢	negotiations(id, document_id, state, participants jsonb), redlines(id, negotiation_id, diff jsonb)
â€¢	anchors(id, doc_version_id, chain, tx_hash, anchor_hash, anchored_at)
â€¢	audit_logs(id, actor_id, action, target_type, target_id, before/after jsonb, ts)
â€¢	evidence_sources(id, url|file, snapshot_uri, license, as_of, locale), evidence_chunks(id, source_id, text, vector, offsets)

Pipelines:
â€¢	Ingestion: file â†’ normalize to DocJSON â†’ segment â†’ embed â†’ classify clauses.
â€¢	Retrieval: prioritize tenant policies/playbooks > clause_library > precedent > public regs; apply recency and credibility.
â€¢	Assessment: compute risk score per clause; detect missing/forbidden/overexposed terms; suggest edits.
â€¢	Proposals: generate redlines + rationale; assemble citations; require HIL approval for highâ€‘risk.
â€¢	Simulation: generate likely counterparty responses across presets (vendorâ€‘friendly/buyerâ€‘friendly/neutral).

Connectors:
â€¢	Eâ€‘sign (DocuSign/Adobe Sign), CLM (e.g., Ironclad/Agiloft) via webhooks/APIs.
â€¢	Storage (S3/GCS) with signed URLs and lifecycle policies.
â€¢	Blockchain RPC (e.g., Ethereum/Polygon via a provider) for optional anchoring; store only hashes/tx metadata.
â€¢	Email (Postmark/SendGrid), Calendar (optional) for negotiation sessions.
Runtime & jobs: Redis for caching/queues; WebSockets for live sessions; idempotent workers for ingestion and anchoring.

2. FRONTEND ARCHITECTURE
â€¢	Next.js 14 (App Router), React 18, TypeScript, Tailwind, shadcn/ui.
â€¢	State/data: React Query for server cache; lightweight Zustand/Context for UI state.
â€¢	Editors: sideâ€‘byâ€‘side diff viewer with tracked changes; clause browser; citation sidebar; policy panel.
â€¢	Realâ€‘time: WebSocket presence, comments, tasks, approvals; optimistic UI for minor edits.
â€¢	Routing: /documents/:id, /negotiations/:id, /library, /policies; i18n for jurisdictional text.
â€¢	Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 AA; keyboardâ€‘first; clear focus states; printable views.

3. DESIGN REQUIREMENTS (UI/UX design based on product & industry)
â€¢	Trustâ€‘first legal UI: calm neutrals, dense yet legible tables, monospace for diffs, colorâ€‘coded redlines.
â€¢	Risk communication: clause risk badges, policy conformance meter, jurisdiction chips.
â€¢	Explainability: expandable rationale with citations to policy/precedent; timestamped sources.
â€¢	Safety affordances: explicit confirmation on highâ€‘risk edits; legalâ€‘advice disclaimer banners.
â€¢	Dark/light modes; printâ€‘perfect exports; highâ€‘contrast option for review marathons.

4. CORE INTEGRATIONS
â€¢	OpenAI + Claude via LangChain (tool calling, structured outputs).
â€¢	OCR provider for scanned PDFs; DOCX/PDF parsing pipeline.
â€¢	CLM and eâ€‘signature connectors; cloud storage for artifacts.
â€¢	SSO (OIDC/SAML) + SCIM; email notifications; optional calendar.
â€¢	Blockchain anchoring provider (public chain RPC) for hash anchoring (no document contents on chain).

5. DELIVERABLES REQUIRED
â€¢	Next.js 14 frontend with negotiation UI (diff, citations, approvals).
â€¢	FastAPI backend with LangGraph orchestration, RAG, policy engine, and collaboration.
â€¢	PostgreSQL schema + pgvector; migrations; seed scripts (sample NDAs/MSAs/DPAs).
